<div class="book-text"><div class="page-rate-widget-box"><span class="rate-points">rating:&nbsp;<span class="number prw54353">+36</span></span><span class="rateup btn btn-default"><a title="I like it" href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.modules.PageRateWidgetModule.listeners.rate(event, 1)">+</a></span><span class="ratedown btn btn-default"><a title="I don't like it" href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.modules.PageRateWidgetModule.listeners.rate(event, -1)">&#8211;</a></span><span class="cancel btn btn-default"><a title="Cancel my vote" href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.modules.PageRateWidgetModule.listeners.cancelVote(event)">x</a></span></div>
<h2 id="toc0"><span>Thread Space</span></h2>
<p>In earôÙlier chapôÙters, we disôÙcussed time travel in terms of tranôÙsiôÙtions beôÙtween world lines, and shown how it can be used to preôÙdict the beôÙhavôÙior of simôÙple time loops. HowôÙever, in orôÙder to unôÙderôÙstand more comôÙplex pheôÙnomôÙena, it is necôÙesôÙsary to genôÙerôÙalôÙize this.</p>
<p><strong>Thread space</strong> refers to the space of all posôÙsiôÙble comôÙbiôÙnaôÙtions of things that could ever ocôÙcur, down to the tiniôÙest deôÙtail of even inôÙtrinôÙsiôÙcally ranôÙdom events (like nuôÙclear deôÙcay or quanôÙtum inôÙterôÙacôÙtions). A sinôÙgle inôÙstance of such a comôÙbiôÙnaôÙtion is reôÙferred to as a <strong>thread</strong>. Note that in relôÙaôÙtivisôÙtic conôÙtexts it's necôÙesôÙsary to conôÙsider each refôÙerôÙence frame havôÙing its own threads, but that will not be covôÙered in this text.</p>
<p>It's also useôÙful to conôÙsider offôÙset threads; that is, given a spaceôÙtime vecôÙtor <span class="math-inline">$\vec x$</span>, then <span class="math-inline">$A + \vec x$</span> is also a thread. We can usuôÙally conôÙsider all the offôÙset threads of a given thread toôÙgether with the first thread, but it beôÙcomes imôÙporôÙtant when disôÙcussing thread disôÙtance and teleôÙporôÙtaôÙtion.</p>
<h4 id="toc1"><span>No ExôÙerôÙcises</span></h4>
<hr />
<h2 id="toc2"><span>The Rzewski Field</span></h2>
<div class="inset">
<p>The Rzewski field was named for <a href="/and-this-one-explains-humes">Dr. CarôÙlos Rzewski</a>, who won the Dirac medal of the FTPI for this disôÙcovôÙery in 1975.</p>
</div>
<p>In orôÙder to propôÙerly unôÙderôÙstand the reôÙlaôÙtionôÙships beôÙtween inôÙdiôÙvidôÙual threads, we also need to inôÙtroôÙduce the <strong>Rzewski field</strong>, one of the funôÙdaôÙmenôÙtal fields in the uniôÙverse. (Note that in some conôÙtexts it may also be reôÙferred to as the <em>subôÙspace field</em>.) ãThe Rzewski field deôÙfines a unique value asôÙsoôÙciôÙated with each point in spaceôÙtime across every thread. It is theôÙoôÙrized to be the unôÙderôÙlyôÙing reaôÙson that that there are points in spaceôÙtime that are disôÙtinct from one anôÙother, as opôÙposed to havôÙing a uniôÙverse conôÙtainôÙing only a sinôÙgle point. This is also what makes difôÙferôÙent threads disôÙtinct from each other, and, most imôÙporôÙtantly for pracôÙtiôÙcal purôÙposes, can be meaôÙsured to diôÙrectly deôÙterôÙmine how simôÙiôÙlar two threads are to each other.</p>
<p>There are a numôÙber of difôÙferôÙent ways this can be meaôÙsured, but one of the most comôÙmon and useôÙful is <strong>thread disôÙtance</strong>, meaôÙsured in humes. In your other courseôÙwork you may have alôÙready enôÙcounôÙtered humes, when meaôÙsurôÙing how &#8220;anomôÙalous&#8221; someôÙthing is with a Kant counter or simôÙiôÙlar deôÙvice. In time travel, we use a difôÙferôÙent tool, the <em>diôÙverôÙgence meôÙter</em>. ãInôÙstead of comôÙparôÙing to a set of fixed pocket diôÙmenôÙsions, a diôÙverôÙgence meôÙter alôÙlows meaôÙsurôÙing thread disôÙtance diôÙrectly relôÙaôÙtive to other threads, and is genôÙerôÙally much more senôÙsiôÙtive.</p>
<p>Note that thread disôÙtance does not diôÙrectly tell us <em>what</em> is difôÙferôÙent beôÙtween two threads, but it does tell us how difôÙferôÙent the threads are, and it can be used to help find where maôÙjor changes may have ocôÙcurred.</p>
<h4 id="toc3"><span>No ExôÙerôÙcises</span></h4>
<hr />
<h2 id="toc4"><span>AlôÙgeôÙbraic PropôÙerôÙties of Thread DisôÙtance</span></h2>
<p>Thread disôÙtance, noôÙtated <span class="math-inline">$d(A,B)$</span> for any given threads A, B, alôÙlows us to deôÙfine a <em>metôÙric space</em> and inôÙduces a topolôÙogy that alôÙlows us to reaôÙson about thread space. While the preôÙcise deôÙtails of the Rizewski field are very imôÙporôÙtant for theôÙoôÙretôÙiôÙcal causalôÙity, for pracôÙtiôÙcal purôÙposes we need not conôÙcern ourôÙselves with it, exôÙcept for a few baôÙsic conôÙcepts.</p>
<p>Since thread disôÙtance is a metôÙric, we have the folôÙlowôÙing propôÙerôÙties:</p>
<ul>
<li><span class="math-inline">$d(A,B)\in\Bbb R$</span> &#8212; Thread disôÙtance is a real numôÙber.</li>
<li><span class="math-inline">$d(A,B)\ge0$</span> &#8212; Thread disôÙtance is non-negôÙaôÙtive.</li>
<li><span class="math-inline">$d(A,A)=0$</span> &#8212; Thread disôÙtance from a thread to itôÙself is zero.</li>
<li><span class="math-inline">$d(A,B)=d(B,A)$</span> &#8212; Thread disôÙtance is reôÙflexôÙive; it's the same meaôÙsured in eiôÙther diôÙrecôÙtion.</li>
<li><span class="math-inline">$d(A,B)\le d(A,C) + d(B,C)$</span> &#8212; Thread disôÙtance obeys the triôÙanôÙgle inôÙequalôÙity; the sum of disôÙtances to some third thread will be at least as large as the diôÙrect disôÙtance beôÙtween two threads. (i.e. There are no &#8216;shortôÙcuts&#8217;.)</li>
</ul>
<p>These propôÙerôÙties are imôÙporôÙtant beôÙcause it alôÙlows us to use anôÙaôÙlytôÙiôÙcal tools to reaôÙson about thread space, and in parôÙticôÙuôÙlar it alôÙlows us to deôÙfine the conôÙcept of <em>thread poôÙtenôÙtial</em>, ãdisôÙcussed in secôÙtion 3.5.</p>
<h4 id="toc5"><span>ExôÙerôÙcises</span></h4>
<ol>
<li>Given that <span class="math-inline">$d(K, Q) = 1.5\,\mathrm{Hm}$</span> and that <span class="math-inline">$d(T, Q) = 7.0\,\mathrm{Hm}$</span>, what is the maxôÙiôÙmum posôÙsiôÙble value for <span class="math-inline">$d(K, T)$</span>?</li>
<li><em>AdôÙvanced</em> Let <span class="math-inline">$f(\vec x) = d(E+\vec x, E)$</span>. Prove that <span class="math-inline">$\nabla\times\nabla f(\vec x)=0$</span>.</li>
</ol>
<hr />
<h2 id="toc6"><span>Thread ConôÙverôÙgence and Time Loops</span></h2>
<div class="inset" style="width:30%;"><img src="http://i.imgur.com/FWHSjH9.png" style="width:100%;display:block;" alt="FWHSjH9.png" class="image" />
<p>An exôÙamôÙple of a thread seôÙquence proôÙjected into 2D conôÙvergôÙing to a world line.</p>
</div>
<p>In chapôÙter 2, we disôÙcussed time loops in terms of world lines, as if each itôÙerôÙaôÙtion of the loop was exôÙactly idenôÙtiôÙcal to the preôÙviôÙous. In pracôÙtice, each itôÙerôÙaôÙtion of a world line will inôÙevitably have at least some small difôÙferôÙence, stemôÙming from BelôÙl's theôÙoôÙrem and the fact that it's imôÙposôÙsiôÙble to obôÙserve anyôÙthing withôÙout changôÙing its state. As a reôÙsult, it makes more sense to talk about world lines as the limôÙits of loop itôÙerôÙaôÙtion.</p>
<p>Given a time loop with a thread seôÙquence <span class="math-inline">$A^{(1)}, B^{(1)}, A^{(2)}, B^{(2)} ...$</span>, then if we can split this seôÙquence up into only fiôÙnitely many conôÙverôÙgent Cauchy seôÙquences, it is posôÙsiôÙble to deôÙfine our world lines as the limôÙits of those seôÙquences. In our exôÙamôÙple, if <span class="math-inline">$A^{(1)}, A^{(2)} ...$</span> and <span class="math-inline">$B^{(1)}, B^{(2)} ...$</span> are both Cauchy seôÙquences, then we can reôÙfer to <span class="math-inline">$A = \lim_{n\to\infty} A^{(n)}$</span> and <span class="math-inline">$B = \lim_{n\to\infty} B^{(n)}$</span> as world lines. In other terms, if afôÙter an arôÙbiôÙtrary numôÙber of times around the loop, it beôÙcomes arôÙbiôÙtrarôÙily hard to disôÙtinôÙguish beôÙtween each <span class="math-inline">$A^{(n)}$</span> and <span class="math-inline">$A^{(n+1)}$</span>, then it still makes sense to conôÙsider them as world lines.</p>
<p>HowôÙever, in some cases it is not posôÙsiôÙble to split up a thread seôÙquence in this way, and any such seôÙquence will inôÙstead conôÙverge to a set of closed curves or higher-orôÙder manôÙiôÙfolds in thread space. These <em>world manôÙiôÙfolds</em> can someôÙtimes still be conôÙsidôÙered in a simôÙiôÙlar way to world lines, but sysôÙtems conôÙtainôÙing world manôÙiôÙfolds are not in genôÙeral solvôÙable usôÙing alôÙgeôÙbraic techôÙniques. Some methôÙods for solvôÙing these more difôÙfiôÙcult sysôÙtems are preôÙsented in chapôÙter 4.</p>
<h4 id="toc7"><span>No ExôÙerôÙcises</span></h4>
<hr />
<h2 id="toc8"><span>Thread PoôÙtenôÙtial</span></h2>
<p>One other imôÙporôÙtant propôÙerty of thread disôÙtance is the way it varies over time and space. In parôÙticôÙuôÙlar, it is conôÙtinôÙuôÙously difôÙferôÙenôÙtiable, and &#8216;at inôÙfinôÙiôÙty&#8217; it is idenôÙtiôÙcally zero. That is:</p>
<span class="equation-number">(1)</span>
<div class="math-equation" id="equation-1">\begin{align} \lim_{|\vec x|\to\infty} d(A+\vec x,B+\vec x)=0 \end{align}</div>
<div class="inset" style="width:30%;">
<p><iframe src="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/unw2n9yt0h?embed" align="" frameborder="" height="" scrolling="" width="" class="" style="width: 100%; border: 1px solid #ccc"></iframe></p>
<p>The thread poôÙtenôÙtial for the event repôÙreôÙsented by the upôÙper (blue) curve is 5 times the lower (red) one, meanôÙing that it is only 1/ã5th as likely.</p>
</div>
<p>MeaôÙsurôÙing thread disôÙtances beôÙtween sepôÙaôÙrate threads is useôÙful for deôÙterôÙminôÙing how simôÙiôÙlar they are, and reaôÙsonôÙing about conôÙverôÙgence. HowôÙever, and in some ways even more imôÙporôÙtantly, we can also meaôÙsure thread disôÙtance beôÙtween points that are only sepôÙaôÙrated by space and time. DoôÙing this makes it posôÙsiôÙble to deôÙfine a poôÙtenôÙtial field based on thread disôÙtance &#8216;to inôÙfinôÙiôÙty&#8217;, called <strong>thread poôÙtenôÙtial</strong> and noôÙtated <span class="math-inline">$\nabla^2 d(E)$</span>, with some exôÙtremely useôÙful propôÙerôÙties.</p>
<span class="equation-number">(2)</span>
<div class="math-equation" id="equation-2">\begin{align} \nabla^2 d(E) = \nabla \cdot \nabla d(E+\vec x, \infty) \end{align}</div>
<p>This quanôÙtity turns out to be enorôÙmously imôÙporôÙtant in later chapôÙters, beôÙcause it alôÙlows us to diôÙrectly reôÙlate the probôÙaôÙbilôÙiôÙties of difôÙferôÙent events to each other:</p>
<span class="equation-number">(3)</span>
<div class="math-equation" id="equation-3">\begin{align} \nabla^2 d(E_1)\, P(E_1) = \nabla^2 d(E_2)\, P(E_2) \end{align}</div>
<p>The raôÙtio of the probôÙaôÙbilôÙiôÙties of two events, is also one of the main deôÙterôÙminôÙing facôÙtors when esôÙtiôÙmatôÙing how easy or difôÙfiôÙcult it would be to change those events via time travel. It also enôÙables us to loôÙcate and map out nearby events that will be susôÙcepôÙtiôÙble to modôÙiôÙfiôÙcaôÙtion, by folôÙlowôÙing the graôÙdiôÙent of the thread poôÙtenôÙtial to its peak.</p>
<div class="blockquote">
<h3 id="toc9"><span>Example 1</span></h3>
<p>We meaôÙsure the thread poôÙtenôÙtial of some event <span class="math-inline">$E$</span> to be:</p>
<span class="equation-number">(4)</span>
<div class="math-equation" id="equation-4">\begin{align} \nabla^2d(E)=1 \end{align}</div>
<p>AfôÙter modôÙiôÙfyôÙing the past so that <span class="math-inline">$E'$</span> ocôÙcurs inôÙstead, we wish to inôÙstead reôÙvert the change to <span class="math-inline">$E$</span>. UnôÙforôÙtuôÙnately, when we meaôÙsure the thread poôÙtenôÙtial:</p>
<span class="equation-number">(5)</span>
<div class="math-equation" id="equation-5">\begin{align} \nabla^2d(E')=0.1 \end{align}</div>
<p>ComôÙputôÙing the relôÙaôÙtive probôÙaôÙbilôÙiôÙties:</p>
<span class="equation-number">(6)</span>
<div class="math-equation" id="equation-6">\begin{align} \frac{P(E)}{P(E')} = \frac{\nabla^2d(E')}{\nabla^2d(E)} = \frac{0.1}{1} = 0.1 \end{align}</div>
<p>Since <span class="math-inline">$E$</span> is only 1/ã10th as likely as <span class="math-inline">$E'$</span>, it will be much more difôÙfiôÙcult to reôÙturn to <span class="math-inline">$E$</span> than it was origôÙiôÙnally to get to <span class="math-inline">$E'$</span>.</p>
</div>
<h4 id="toc10"><span>No ExôÙerôÙcises</span></h4>
</div>
<hr />
